Description.val:
This line item funds modifications to the E-6 Mercury aircraft to improve mission capability and readiness.  All sixteen (16) aircraft, unless otherwise noted in the E-6 fleet will receive each modification.  The E-6 is a manned airborne communications platform designed to provide a survivable, endurable, and reliable airborne Command and Control Communications capability in support of the President, Secretary of Defense, and United States strategic and non-strategic forces.  

-Safety Deficiencies (OSIP 008-02) corrects high risk aircraft safety hazards to protect personnel and equipment enabling mission readiness.  

-Tech Insertion (OSIP 003-04) corrects aircraft obsolescence, supportability, weight management and interoperability deficiencies through new technology insertion enabling mission readiness and mandate compliance. 

-Service Life Extension Program (OSIP 003-07) extends the service life of the aircraft to 2038+ through airframe strengthening and structural data recording and analysis.  

-Communications Upgrade (OSIP 012-07) installs expanded aircraft digital communication paths and processing to improve airborne command post operations and modernizes direct over-the-horizon communications links to deployed strategic forces.  

-Block I (OSIP 008-10) corrects Airborne Command Post (ABNCP) operational test deficiencies to improve mission capability, readiness and legacy system obsolescence. 

-Multi-Role Tactical Common Data Link (OSIP 013-10) installs expanded aircraft communication bandwidth capability required to interoperate with United States Strategic Command's National Command and Control Architecture.  

-Auxiliary Power Unit (APU) (OSIP 002-12) corrects airborne command post operational test deficiencies by installing an improved APU to meet increased aircraft power requirements.  

-Family of Advanced Beyond-Line-of-Sight Terminals/Presidential and National Voice Conferencing (FAB-T/PNVC) (OSIP 014-14) replaces obsolete Military Strategic Tactical Relay terminals with improved FAB-T and replaces Secure Emergency Conferencing Network with PNVC.  

-Mission Systems (OSIP 011-21) corrects mission systems obsolescence, supportability, and interoperability deficiencies through technology insertion of commercial and government off the shelf (COTs/GOTs) systems.

Justification.val: The FY 2020 funding request was increased by $5.316 million due to Safety Deficiencies (OSIP 008-02) for Kapton Lower Lobe installations, Tech Insertion (OSIP 003-04) for Fuel Tank Sealant Upgrade installations, Service Life Extension program (SLEP) (OSIP 003-07) for Crash Survivable Flight Incident Recorder System(CSFIR) installation, Multi-Role Tactical Common Data Link (OSIP 013-10) installations, Auxiliary Power Unit (APU) (OSIP 002-12) installations, Family of Advanced Beyond-Line-of-Sight Terminals/Presidential and National Voice Conferencing (FAB-T/PNVC) (OSIP 014-14) installations.  The FY 2020 funding request was reduced by $7.769 million to account for the availability of prior year execution balances.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: Technology Insertion corrects aircraft systems obsolescence, supportability, and interoperability deficiencies as well as providing weight savings initiatives through technology insertion of commercial and government off the shelf (COTs/GOTs) system integration onto the E-6B. Integration of already qualified airborne systems will be primary solution sets, but if required the ruggedization of the COTs/GOTs from land or water fielded systems may be pursued. Carbon Brakes integrates prior DoD-135/707 type brakes to the E-6B. Seats integrates DoD approved mission seats to meet E-6B crash load requirements. ADS-B Out integrates production COTs/GOTs to address Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) civil navigation requirements by calendar year 2020. Global Positioning System (GPS) M Code/Advanced Digital Antenna Production (ADAP) integrates production GOTs systems to correct aircraft GPS deficiencies and improve readiness. Cockpit Update (CU) integrates follow-on Boeing 737 and P-8A hardware to address obsolescence and additional civil navigation requirements. Fuel Tank Sealant Upgrade (FTSU) utilizes new commercially proven processes and materials to correct fuel system leaks caused by age and operational hours. Aircraft (AC) Electrical will integrate updated technology to the aircraft power generation and distribution system to improve power quality and distribution, and reduce aircraft weight.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES: Carbon Brake installs in PY-FY23 based on fleet aircraft availability. Seat installs in FY17-FY23 based on fleet aircraft availability. CU A-kit buys beyond FYDP; B kit buys beyond FYDP; with installs beyond FYDP. FTSU A-kit buys in FY19-FY23; with installs in FY19-FY23. Aircraft Electrical A-kit buys FY23 to beyond FYDP; B-kit buys FY23 to beyond FYDP; with installs in FY24 to beyond FYDP. GPS M Code/ADAP A-kit buys in FY20 to beyond FYDP.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION:  Service Life Extension Program (SLEP) extends the service life of the aircraft to 2038+ through airframe strengthening, structural data recording and analysis, and just in time modifications to prevent aircraft grounding due to fatigue.  Modifications include, but not limited to:  SLEP Phase 1; Individual Aircraft Tracking System (IATS); Crash Survivable Flight Incident Recorder System (CSFIRS) Phase 2; Runway Survey Analysis; and SLEP Phase 1B.  IATS will integrate the data collected from already installed Digital Flight Data Acquisition Unit (DFDAU) to support the Aircraft Structural Integrity Program along with data collected from a representative sample of E-6Bs (2 aircraft) during a limited period of time.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES: IATS NRE PY-FY18, A-kit buys in FY18 and installs in FY18-FY19.  SLEP Phase 1B NRE FY17-FY18, kit buys FY18 to beyond FYDP, and installs FY19 to beyond FYDP; CSFIRS Phase 2 NRE FY18-FY19, kit buys in FY20-FY22 and installs FY20-FY22.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION:  Installs expanded aircraft digital communication paths and processing to improve airborne command post operations and modernizes direct over-the-horizon communications links to deployed strategic forces.  Internet Protocol (IP) connectivity and wideband communication capability to enable voice, video and data services is mission critical to command and control operations.  Modifications include: IP Phase 1, International Marine/Maritime Satellite (INMARSAT); IP Phase 3, removal of Utility Trailing Wire Antenna (UTWA); Key Generator Receiver (KGR)-72; and High Power Transmit Set (HPTS) Modernization Program.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES:  KGR-72 NRE in FY17-FY18. KGR-72 Life of Type Buy production kit buy in FY19 with production installs in FY19-FY22. HPTS Modernization NRE begins in FY19-FY22 with procurement of kits FY22-FYDP and production installs in FY23-FYDP.  High Frequency Automatic Link Establishment (HF-ALE) requirements are evolving and funding was realigned by the Department of the Navy for higher priority requirements.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION:  The Auxiliary Power Unit (APU) incorporates safety, capacity and life-limiting propulsion and power corrective actions to resolve safety and readiness concerns.  Corrections to design deficiencies found during post production test and evaluation and discovered during fleet operations have resulted in safety and reliability degradations that must be corrected.  The requirement to upgrade or modify the APU is critical in maintaining sustainable fleet reliability, safety, and performance and is necessary to meet established mission requirements.

DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: Family of Advanced Beyond-Line-of-Sight Terminals (FAB-T) and Presidential and National Voice Conferencing (PNVC) are U.S. Air Force (USAF) programs of record. E-6B integration NRE for FAB-T and PNVC includes Red Switch (RS) integration, which is required for PNVC capability.

Description.val:
DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: Mission Systems corrects mission systems obsolescence, supportability, and interoperability deficiencies through technology insertion of commercial and government off the shelf (COTs/GOTs)
system integration onto the E-6B. Integration of already qualified airborne systems will be primary solution sets, but if required the ruggedization of the COTs/GOTs from land or water fielded systems may be pursued. Mission
Operations Monitor (MOM) will update already installed E-6B systems with the ability to monitor and record critical parameters to ensure mission accomplishment and provide for accurate and timely post mission evaluations.
Additional hardware for more robust monitoring may be added to the aircraft. Airborne Launch Control System-Replacement (ALCS-R) will integrate an Air Force procured system onto the E-6B to replace the current ALCS which
is going obsolete. 64 Bit will address 32 bit hardware/software obsolescence and associated cyber vulnerabilities by re-hosting latest versions of software on a 64 bit compliant hardware architecture.

DEVELOPMENT STATUS/MAJOR DEVELOPMENT MILESTONES: ALCS-R NRE FY21-FYDP, ALCS-R A & B kit buys in FY22-FYDP with installs in FY23-FYDP.  64 Bit NRE FY21-FYDP, 64 Bit A & B Kits and installs beyond FYDP. MOM NRE FY24-FYDP, MOM A & B Kits and installs beyond FYDP.
